nd those of men like him. He shows what it was like for these young men to grow up gay in an immigrant family, to be the one gay person in their school and ethnic community, and to be a person of color in predominantly White gay spaces. Brown and Gay in LA is an homage to second-generation gay men and their radical redefinition of what it means to be gay, to be a man, to be a person of color, and, ultimately, what it means to be an American.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAsian American gay peoplezCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aGay menzCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aMexican American gay peoplezCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh  aAcceptance.  aAsian American.  aBody.  aBullying.  aChildhood.  aClass.  aCollege.  aComing out.  aCommunity.  aCovering.  aCultural Centers.  aEducation.  aEthnicity.  aFamily.  aFilipino.  aGay.  aGayborhoods.  aGender.  aHigher Education.  aImmigration.  aIntersectionality.  aLGBTQ.  aLatino.  aMasculinity.  aQueer.  aRace.  aRacism.  aReligion.  aRespectability.  aSexualities.  aSexuality.  aSizeism.  aSocial Media.  aStudent Organizations.  aTherapy.  aTransgender.  aTransnational.  aUrban.  aWhiteness.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479837366.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479837366423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479837366/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles